  <table cellpadding=3D0 cellspacing=3D0 width=3D"100%">
   <tr>
    <td><![endif]>
    <div>
    <p class=3DMsoNormal>So, what does the DNS rule of threes do? It creates
    redundancy for high availability DNS resolution within your network. Wh=
ich
    allows for services to keep working even when one or more DNS servers f=
ail.
    </p>
    <p class=3DMsoNormal>What issues can it cause? If you are behind a <span
    class=3DSpellE>natted</span> firewall with local servers. You will only=
 show
    your public IP address to public resolvers. Therefore, only show your
    public IP to other services online. This can lead to rate limiting or
    blocking due to the high <span class=3DGramE>amount</span> of requests.=
 </p>
    </div>
    <![if !mso]></td>
   </tr>
  </table>
  <![endif]></v:textbox>
